The bird described above exhibits so many points of distinc- tion from the preceding specieS, that we have ranked it as sepa- rate. Its locality also, which is different from that of the other specieS, serves to strengthen us in this opinion. The chief dif- ference consists in the inferior size of our bird, all the specimens we have seen of the former Species being about thirteen inches in length ; in the darkness of the asli-colour on the back ; in the narrowness of the frontal band, and particularly in the white colour of the mentum.
